passages.text: FY25 First Take: Slight mison JPMR (more downgrading, better claims inflation), Guidance for FY26 very modestly weaker / broadly in line with JPMF at first glance

MPL's FY25 result was a slight miss vs our numbers and consensus for management NPAT. Health Insurance operating profit was in line driven by low claims inflation, but higher downgrading, and weaker than guided ARHI volume growth of system growth. Medibank Health was a slight miss on consensus.

FY26 outlook of \(2.6 - 2.9\%\) claims per policy growth, and increased downgrading from FY25 \(0.9\%\) - and flat to improving MER- suggests flattish Net margins taking into account premium rate increase of \(3.99\%\) for FY25. This is in line with JPMF.
Dividend was a miss on JPMF but in line with consensus and capital ratio is strong.

MPL for FY25 reported 1) Adjusted Profit after tax (before abnormals) of \(\) 618.7m\(\)\\(623.5m\); Cons \(\) 628.2m\(\); 2) Operating margin (health insurance) of \(9.0\%\) (JPMF \(9.1\%\) ; Cons \(9.0\%\) ); 3) Health Insurance operating profit of \(\) 741.5m\(\)\\(752.5m\); Cons \(\) 741.0m\(\); 4) DPS (cps) of 18.0 (JPMF 18.4; Cons 18.0); 5) Complementary services segment profit of\)\\(76.7m\) (JPMF \(\) 76.5m\(\); Cons\)\\(79.8m\)).

Key positives: (1) Good Medibank Health result - in line with JPMF but slight miss on consensus; (2) Strong non- resident growth of \(3.1\%\) in FY25; (3) Increased give backs (now \(\) 228m\(from\)\\(160m\) announced in Feb). Policy needs to be there on 30 June, and get cash in September 2025. This will help retention. NPS also increased a bit and usage of live better rewards keeps increasing; (4) Claims inflation per policy very low - \(2.2\% - vs guidance of 2.4 - 2.6\%\); (5) Cash claims were \(\) 74.8m\(below management basis in FY25 - was\) \ \(43m\) in 1H25 - so still good buffers seen in 2H. Suggests starting point for FY26 is good; (6) Improving lapse in FY25 - as cyber issues roll off; (7) FY26 Guidance broadly in line / maybe slightly less than JPMF: Claims inflation 2.6 - 2.9%, downgrading increasing and flat to reducing MER and for market share growth in ARHI but expecting system to moderate (suggests broadly stable Net margins). Still expecting Medibank Health to grow but now low- doublet digit.

Key negatives: (1) Slight management NPAT miss on JPMF and consensus - driven by operating profit slight miss and investment income; (2) ARHI net policy growth of \(1.4\%\) for FY25 appears less than market for 2H (implies \(0.1\%\) for MPL - whilst we think market was \(1.2\%\) ); (3) Downgrading in ARHI increased. Was \(0.9\%\) in FY25, vs \(0.5\%\) in 1H. Expecting it to increase in FY26; (4) Health insurance expenses slightly higher than JPMF and guidance (was \(\) 650m\(guidance - now\) \ \(655m\) ); (5) dividend slight miss on JPM but in line with consensus. Capital OK; (6) MPL calling out some unsustainable industry practices like discounting, use of aggregators; (7) MPL also
MPL.AX,MPLAU Price (27 Aug 25):A\\$5.15 Price Target (Jun- 26):A\\$5.10

saying competition increasing in worker and visitor segment; (8) COVID- 19 equity reserve reduced to 0 - as previously guided. This removes some source of buffers; (9) Reserve assumptions and CHE assumptions weaker than FY24.

Resident health insurance Industry growth: MPL anticipates moderating industry growth in FY26 relative to FY25 and they aim to grow market share with a disciplined approach, particularly in the Medibank brand.
- Management Expense Ratio (MER) expected to be flat to moderately improving into FY26. Targeting \(\) 10\mathrm{mn}\$ productivity savings in FY26.
- Downgrading expected to deteriorate further from the \(0.9\%\) in FY25.
- Claims: Claims per policy unit growth in FY26 is expected to be between \(2.6\%\) and \(2.9\%\)
- Non-resident health insurance customer growth: Expect solid policy unit growth to continue in FY26.
- Medibank Health: MPL expects to achieve low double-digit organic operating profit growth.
- M&A investments are targeted towards the top end of the \(\) 150\$ million - \(\) 250\$ million range for FY24 - FY26, focusing on long-term value creation.
- FY26 Cyber Costs of \(\) 35\mathrm{mn}\$ (JPMF FY26 \(\) 40\mathrm{mn}\$
- Additional Segment-specific Comments:

- Resident Health Insurance: Focus on sustainable and disciplined growth by improving retention, particularly in AHM, through digital investment and integrated customer propositions. Growth in priority segments, including the corporate segment, and deepening brand differentiation with new products and services.- Non-Resident Business: Further differentiation and investment in product value, with a focus on students, workers, and visitors. Lifecycle management opportunities for customers transitioning to Australian residents.- Medibank Health: Delivering strong organic growth potential with performance uplift in healthcare services, meeting more health insurance customer needs, and scaling existing programs to a broader set of payors.

Medibank Private Limited (Neutral; Price Target: A\(5.10)

Medibank's health insurance division has had strong margin trends in recent periods, driven by a bounce- back in non- resident health profits, but with some margin expansion in resident insurance as well. Medibank Health has had mixed success in growing in the past, but appears to have gained traction from FY24 onwards, and this is where MPL is investing incremental capital. MPL's guidance seems to flag broadly flat underlying resident gross margins in FY24 and non- resident margin expansion. MPL still has some COVID- 19 balance sheet buffers that can assist in smoothing claims, if required. MPL's past cyber issues suggest some caution is needed. We maintain our Neutral rating.

Our Jun- 26 DCF- based PT is A\(5.10, at a slight 2.1% discount to our A\)5.21 DCF valuation to reflect some risks from the pending legal cases relating to the cyber incident, which has perhaps also been responsible for MPL's slower- than- system growth in a competitive environment in recent periods. We use a cost of equity of 9.3%, a terminal growth rate of 3.3%, an investment earnings rate on surplus capital of 4%, and franking credits valued at 70% of face value.

- Targeted expense reductions are not achieved.- The overseas business deteriorates further.- More people drop out of private health insurance (PHI) than we expect post-COVID-19.- A harsh interpretation of profiting from COVID-19 by the Department of Health.- Cyber risks, including class actions and a lack of growth because of brand damage.
Key upside risks include:

- Cyber risk from the recent hack of systems reducing.- MPL chooses to build up a large claims reserve from COVID-19 changes, affecting ancillary and elective (hospital) claims, and eventually releases some of this to profit (or otherwise increases its target margins).- Investors may like the relatively defensive nature of MPL in an environment where many industries will face significant stress.- The ALP government reduces its scrutiny of premium rates, allowing margins to be maintained or even expand in a post-COVID-19 world where there is considerable uncertainty.- MPL reduces claims inflation in the industry below peers' and thereby offsets the low rate increases.- MPL makes some accretive acquisitions and leverages its balance sheet, which boosts EPS growth. The balance sheet is currently under-geared vs. peers'.- A turnaround in industry participation trends.- Favourable legislation changes by the government, encouraging participation to increase in the system or reducing claims costs.- A reduction in industry competition.
